11. ...Bb7?! doesn't work properly. Better is to defend the knight with the c pawn (11. ...c6). With 12. Qf3 White bring the match in his favor. It works also 12. d4 (as in the game). In GK database only 60 times over about 1100 Marshall Attacks, at this point, Black played 11. ...Bb7.

Maybe is better to exchange the rooks (14. Rxe8+) to gain a development move. The spirit of the Marshall is to open the game and play a pawn sacrifice for mobility and development. In this game Black didn't play at 100% and White could regain time, remaining with a pawn up.

After 14. Rxe8+ Qxe8 the Black queen in e8 needs a second move to find a better place.
